00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:01.520
[Amit Varma]: us. So now we're recording this on the 23rd of July and the 25th, obviously the elections

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:07.400
[Amit Varma]: in Pakistan. So what I wanted this episode to be about is not so much what the outcome

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:11.680
[Amit Varma]: will be, because it will be known by the time you listen to it, but we don't know it yet.

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:19.120
[Amit Varma]: But more about what is the landscape of politics and electoral politics in Pakistan and how

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:25.640
[Amit Varma]: it's kind of evolved. So Pranay, just give me sort of a quick update, like I'm speaking

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:31.680
[Amit Varma]: purely from a layman's perspective. What is Pakistani democracy? Is there such a thing?

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:38.520
[Guest 2]: The Pakistani democracy is quite elusive, actually. And that's been perplexing for many

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:45.960
[Guest 2]: of the people around. And the way we've tried to characterize it is that Pakistan is actually

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:51.400
[Guest 2]: not one geopolitical entity, but two of them. One is the putative state of Pakistan, which

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:57.680
[Guest 2]: actually has its flag, a PM, a PM's car, and all that paraphernalia with it. But the more

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:02.240
[Guest 2]: important one is something what we call the military jihadi complex. Now, the way we define

00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:11.320
[Guest 2]: it is that it is a dynamic syndicate of the military, militants, the jihadists, the radicalists,

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:17.960
[Guest 2]: and political economic structures, which basically have their own foreign policy and domestic

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:24.320
[Guest 2]: policies. And they try to assert their relative dominance over this entire thing called Pakistan.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:31.960
[Guest 2]: So it is this MJC or the military jihadi complex, which actually is in control of the corridors

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:37.520
[Guest 2]: of power in Pakistan, and it is the one which determines what will happen. And even in this

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:42.680
[Guest 2]: election, if you see it, the most important opinion that matters is not the one that comes

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:47.920
[Guest 2]: out of opinion polls, but the opinion of the military, and the military seems to have made

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:53.320
[Amit Varma]: its choice. So what's really the history of this military jihadi complex? Like, it hasn't

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:58.580
[Amit Varma]: always existed, I'm assuming. But at the same time, like, would you say that the dominance

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:02.760
[Amit Varma]: of the military was something written in the DNA of the Pakistan state in terms of how

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:03.760
[Guest 2]: it was formed?

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest 2]: Yes, actually, it is, it has been existing since the emergence of Pakistan. And in fact,

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:16.560
[Guest 2]: there is a great book by Steve Wilkinson called Army and the Nation. And it tries to lay out

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:21.920
[Guest 2]: a comparison between the history of the Indian Army and the history of Pakistani Army and

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:28.920
[Guest 2]: why both of them diverge in terms of the political roles that armies play in both states. And

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:34.480
[Guest 2]: it's a fascinating account of that. And the military jihadi complex has its root right

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:39.200
[Guest 2]: from the emergence of Pakistan. There have been several constitutions that Pakistan has

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:45.880
[Guest 2]: had several stages where the military was in direct control of the government. And even

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:52.160
[Guest 2]: now, even though there is something called a Pakistani PM, do you know who's the Pakistani

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:54.200
[Guest 2]: PM now, for example?

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:55.680
[Guest 2]: Give me a minute while I Google it.

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:03.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah, right. You need to Google it. I think you might know the PM of some other neighboring

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:07.200
[Guest 2]: state, but it's difficult. Let's say Maldives, you would know who is right. But in Pakistan,

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:12.120
[Guest 2]: it's difficult because the current guy who's been installed is someone who's not even a

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:19.640
[Guest 2]: big guy in his own political party. He was only installed because Nawaz Sharif sort of

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:24.760
[Guest 2]: confronted the Pakistani military and the military jihadi complex thought that he was

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:29.720
[Guest 2]: getting too big for his shoes. And hence he was booted out. So if I have to say what are

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:35.200
[Guest 2]: the broad trends that have taken place over the last few years, let's look at it first

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:41.960
[Guest 2]: from a foreign policy angle of Pakistan. One, the narrative that the MJC has been selling

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:48.680
[Guest 2]: all these years that they are the protectors of Pakistan and the world would be worse off

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:53.600
[Guest 2]: if they weren't there. That kind of narrative has weakened over the last few years. The

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:58.400
[Guest 2]: Americans who are backing the Pakistani military just because they thought there was no better

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:03.520
[Guest 2]: option, they chose to believe so, are also frustrated with it. So if you see over the

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:11.360
[Guest 2]: last few years, the aid that Pakistan army got has significantly declined. So from a

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:17.320
[Guest 2]: foreign policy angle, there is a pressure. The amount of options that Pakistani army

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:24.280
[Guest 2]: had have reduced now. That's one big thing. In the domestic side, what you saw was last

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:31.000
[Guest 2]: time Nawaz Sharif, his party called the Pakistan Muslim League, Nawaz, won a landslide elections.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:38.040
[Guest 2]: They won around 178 seats out of 342. And it was the first time when a democratic transition

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:44.000
[Guest 2]: actually took place from one democratic party to the other. Big, big event right after 70

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:50.080
[Guest 2]: years. And even though that happened, after that Nawaz Sharif sort of did a lot of things

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:56.520
[Guest 2]: to change Pakistan and most importantly, and where the Pakistani military didn't like it

00:08:56.520 --> 00:09:02.840
[Guest 2]: is where he started questioning the ISI, etc. on what they have been doing in regulating

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:08.360
[Guest 2]: the jihadists. And this came out as a leaked report in a famous newspaper called Dawn.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:15.040
[Guest 2]: And that's when the Pakistani military started to go behind him. And hence he was overthrown.

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:20.040
[Guest 2]: And he was forced to exit. There was a non entity was made the PM. So these are the two

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:24.440
[Guest 2]: things. The third one is what is happening on the Pakistani border with Afghanistan,

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:29.440
[Guest 2]: which I guess Hamsini can tell you better. Yeah, something that I wanted to talk about

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:36.600
[Guest 1]: was the rise of the Pashtun Taifus movement. So what's been happening is that since 2015,

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:41.840
[Guest 1]: there's been supposedly a crackdown on the Tariq-e-Taliban Pakistan. And so the Pakistan

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:49.120
[Guest 1]: army launched something called Operation Zarb-e-Azab. And this meant that a lot of people who were

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:54.600
[Guest 1]: in the area were arbitrarily detained and harassed and all of that. And this is not

00:09:54.600 --> 00:10:00.960
[Guest 1]: new also in the federally administrated tribal areas of FATA, which comes under, it doesn't

00:10:00.960 --> 00:10:06.000
[Guest 1]: come under the Pakistani constitution. So what happened is from 2015, there have been

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.040
[Guest 2]: small protests. Just to correct, it does come under the Pakistani constitution, but the

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:16.080
[Guest 2]: laws which apply to these people are different from the laws that apply to the other Pakistanis.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:22.240
[Guest 2]: So there is something called the FCR and their draconian laws. For example, one person doesn't

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:26.560
[Guest 2]: have one vote in those areas, whereas the other Pakistanis have. Here there is something

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:31.520
[Guest 2]: called a community vote, things like that. Really crazy colonial stuff, which still continues

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:35.280
[Guest 1]: to this. Yeah. And another thing is if you do something, then members of your family

00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:40.720
[Guest 1]: will be detained and so on. So they are really draconian laws. So what's happened over the

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:46.980
[Guest 1]: last year is that this movement started calling for, you know, dignity for the rights of Pashtuns.

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:52.200
[Guest 1]: And it's the first grassroots movement in recent history in Pakistan that's managed

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:57.600
[Guest 1]: to affect an outcome that the Pakistan army was not really favorable to. So one of the

00:10:57.600 --> 00:11:03.880
[Guest 1]: things that they were able to do about a month ago was merge two provinces in Pakistan, Khyber

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:08.880
[Guest 1]: Pakhtunkhwa and FATA. And this has been a demand for a very long time so that there

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:12.160
[Guest 1]: would be better governance and so on. But this is the first time that the change has

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:18.600
[Guest 1]: actually been mandated. And this goes on to show that there is a lot of dissatisfaction

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:22.480
[Guest 1]: on the ground. The people aren't really happy with the way that the civilian government

00:11:22.480 --> 00:11:26.600
[Guest 1]: has been acting simply because the civilian government does not have a lot of power.

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:31.480
[Amit Varma]: And correct me if I'm wrong, but one sense in which this uprising is different from past

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:37.880
[Amit Varma]: uprisings is that past uprisings focused to a certain extent on identity politics and

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:42.600
[Amit Varma]: Pashtuns versus arrest and so on. While this was really focused strongly on individual

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:46.800
[Amit Varma]: rights and on just being treated as citizens and so on. Is that a correct formulation?

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:52.400
[Guest 2]: No, I would suggest it is still largely it is being seen as a Pashtun movement itself.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:57.240
[Guest 2]: The word itself means Pashtun protection movement. But are they agitating for the same sort of

00:11:57.240 --> 00:12:02.320
[Guest 2]: things they were in the past? Yeah, it's not that they are arguing for a Pashtunistan or

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:08.000
[Guest 2]: anything like that. They are arguing for Pashtuns to have the same rights that other Pakistanis

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:14.400
[Guest 2]: have, essentially that. And the unique thing about this is that the leadership is not affiliated

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:20.200
[Guest 2]: with any political party. So it's tough for the Pakistani army to curb it. They have immense

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:24.680
[Guest 2]: amount of instruments to curb it, right. And the military jadhi complex excels in that

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:30.520
[Guest 2]: they can manufacture charges, get forced disappearances. It's a very famous term in Pakistan, which

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:36.720
[Guest 2]: is called namalu mafrads. These are unidentified persons, they emerge out of nowhere, and they

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:41.840
[Guest 2]: will just abduct you. Very, very common happened to a lot of Pashtuns. And in fact, that is

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:47.280
[Guest 2]: why this entire movement started. And the leader of this, for example, is a guy called

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:53.920
[Guest 2]: Manzoor Pashteen. He's a young chap has no political history. But he went around Fata

00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:59.920
[Guest 2]: and there was a march, a lot of people joined him on the way. So it's what Hamsini said

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:05.320
[Guest 2]: a grassroots movement, which really caught on and the Pakistani army was caught unawares.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:10.320
[Guest 1]: Yeah, and what the movement has done differently from other movements, as Pranay said, is that

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:16.160
[Guest 1]: it didn't take up any political affiliations, even at the end of it after the two provinces

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:21.040
[Guest 1]: were merged, and a lot of people were saying, you know, what next for the movement? The

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:25.400
[Guest 1]: leaders of the movement were saying maybe individuals will take up political contest

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:29.960
[Guest 1]: if they want to, but the movement as such is not going to back anyone. And while it

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:35.160
[Guest 1]: was happening, it was suddenly seen as you know, an important vote that they had never

00:13:35.160 --> 00:13:41.080
[Guest 1]: counted before on because traditionally Pashtun votes go to the PTI that works, the Pakistan

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:48.200
[Guest 1]: Tehreek-e-Insaf, that is in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. So this was seen as a new demographic that

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:53.080
[Guest 1]: has never come to the foray before in Pakistan.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:58.440
[Amit Varma]: And just sort of going back to the first point you made, Pranay, about the army no longer

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.080
[Amit Varma]: the military jihadi complex been weakened over the last few years. And I remember the

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:10.360
[Amit Varma]: early 2000s before 9-11, Pakistan was economically pretty much on the verge of collapse and someone

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:15.720
[Amit Varma]: like I visited Pakistan to cover the Indian cricket tour of 2006. And I'd also written

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:19.440
[Amit Varma]: for the Wall Street Journal and so on in that time. And I remember someone at that point

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:25.080
[Amit Varma]: telling me that we think of, we don't call Al-Qaeda Al-Qaeda, we call it Al-Faida. Because

00:14:25.080 --> 00:14:32.440
[Amit Varma]: what happened with that was that the army suddenly got a spurt of validation and you

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:36.640
[Amit Varma]: know, it could justify itself in much stronger times, in much stronger terms and a lot of

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:41.560
[Amit Varma]: funds poured in from abroad because you obviously looked as Pakistan as a key ally in the war

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:47.280
[Amit Varma]: against terror and the military jihadi complex just grew stronger. Now, one reason for the

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:50.960
[Amit Varma]: military jihadi complex growing weaker, obviously, is that the West has figured out that these

00:14:50.960 --> 00:14:58.880
[Amit Varma]: guys are not allies, they are playing a double game. But is it also the case that even domestically,

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:02.360
[Amit Varma]: people are more empowered or more disillusioned against the army? Is it like a two way thing

00:15:02.360 --> 00:15:10.560
[Guest 2]: happening here? Yes, that's true for some section because look at it like this. So Pakistani

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:15.920
[Guest 2]: military jihadi complex, everyone now knows that they are the ones who are in the driver's

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:22.240
[Guest 2]: seat. And in spite of them being in the driver's seat, things haven't changed a lot, right.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:28.360
[Guest 2]: And in fact, the gap between India and Pakistan has also been widened significantly. So in

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:33.160
[Guest 2]: a sense, there is this disillusionment that whatever we were promised, and the military

00:15:33.160 --> 00:15:39.040
[Guest 2]: being the protectors of the ideological frontiers have not delivered. So there is that sense

00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:45.240
[Guest 2]: of alienation which has come in. But because the military jihadi complex is still the most

00:15:45.240 --> 00:15:50.320
[Guest 2]: powerful formation, it can, you know, there are these, for example, every year, there

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:55.920
[Guest 2]: are these surveys, which keep getting held everywhere. And still Pakistani army gets

00:15:55.920 --> 00:16:03.120
[Guest 2]: some 75% ratings in the most trusted institution of Pakistan and all that. So that kind of

00:16:03.120 --> 00:16:08.240
[Guest 2]: continues. But I guess yes, there has been some disillusionment that we aren't getting

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:12.840
[Guest 2]: what we are. Most recent example, actually, like just yesterday, there have been street

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:20.160
[Guest 2]: protests in Punjab, people saying ISI Murdabad and all that. That's very, very rare for it

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:27.160
[Guest 2]: to happen in Punjab. Second, what has also changed the fact is that there have been terrorist

00:16:27.160 --> 00:16:33.480
[Guest 2]: attacks in the heartland of Punjab over the last few years. So that again, has set a question

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:39.080
[Guest 2]: back in the army's court that what happened, you were the guys who are going to protect

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:44.640
[Guest 2]: us against India and against all the terrorists. But now, even the gardens of you know, there

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:50.920
[Guest 2]: was an attack in a park in Punjab in Lahore. So even those places aren't safe anymore.

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:56.720
[Guest 2]: So that has sort of weakened domestically. And would it be your case that you know, when

00:16:56.720 --> 00:17:00.740
[Amit Varma]: Indians typically think of Pakistan as an enemy nation, what they actually thinking

00:17:00.740 --> 00:17:05.640
[Amit Varma]: of is a military jihadi complex, and not so much the you know, like Pakistan civil society

00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:10.880
[Amit Varma]: at this point, seems fairly fed up themselves of the military jihadi complex.

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:16.000
[Guest 2]: No, that's a very good point. Actually, that's why I was trying to say that look at Pakistan

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:23.320
[Guest 2]: as two entities, there is this one entity, which you can't probably, you know, sort of

00:17:23.320 --> 00:17:27.680
[Guest 2]: get you on your side, because they have defined their existence as opposing you. And that's

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:33.560
[Guest 2]: a military jihadi complex, right. So maybe the long term solution for the for that entity

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:39.280
[Guest 2]: is just that resist, we need to resist it for now and hope that we dismantle it in the

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:47.000
[Guest 2]: future or it gets dismantled on its own. But the other side is not inherently inimical

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:52.800
[Guest 2]: to India or might not be so it at least it can be changed. And an evidence for that is

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:59.640
[Guest 2]: like what you see happening in a Kashmir, for example, over the last two, three years,

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:07.120
[Guest 2]: Pakistan could have done a lot more if it wanted to. And I it's my sort of assertion

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:12.680
[Guest 2]: that actually they haven't done a lot. And a lot of problems which are of the recent

00:18:12.680 --> 00:18:18.440
[Guest 2]: times are our own problems and the way we've handled Kashmir politically, but Pakistan

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:23.720
[Guest 2]: has been a peripheral player in this, but it's not been the main person which is doing

00:18:23.720 --> 00:18:26.600
[Guest 2]: things from behind, which was the case a few years ago,

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:29.680
[Guest 2]: Your case is if they wanted to, they could have, they could have and they didn't. So

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:36.000
[Guest 2]: why didn't they? They didn't because as you see, last few years, Nawaz Sharif was the

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:43.040
[Guest 2]: one who was trying to assert himself politically. And there were some overtures on both sides.

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:49.080
[Guest 2]: And they sort of tried to figure it out that, you know, maybe we need to get our acts in

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:53.280
[Guest 2]: the domestic sphere first together and then see what we have to do with India. So there

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:58.880
[Guest 2]: was and remember the terrorism increased significantly within Pakistan, right? So there was backlash

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:04.600
[Guest 2]: internally as well. If Punjab is getting bombed internally, they said, how can we support

00:19:04.600 --> 00:19:09.920
[Guest 2]: terrorism elsewhere? So this entire narrative of Pakistan having backing terrorist elements

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:14.360
[Guest 2]: sort of had weakened over the last few years, right?

00:19:14.360 --> 00:19:19.840
[Guest 1]: And do you think that this is one of the reasons Nawaz Sharif also faced pushback from the

00:19:19.840 --> 00:19:25.120
[Guest 1]: army that he was trying to control terrorism and didn't let the terrorists affect what

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:26.120
[Guest 2]: was happening?

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:30.720
[Guest 2]: He was questioning those guys. And that's what the report in Dawn said. And that was

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:37.000
[Guest 2]: a bit too much to ask. And that's why what happened and he was declared that he was not

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:38.760
[Guest 2]: sadiq and amin, right?

00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:44.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, what is a sadiq and amin? You told me before you began recording, but for the benefit

00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:45.520
[Guest 2]: of the listeners.

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:51.760
[Guest 2]: It's fascinating Pakistan has so current constitution, which is in force in Pakistan was the one

00:19:51.760 --> 00:20:00.320
[Guest 2]: which started in 1973. And after that, an article was inserted in Zia ul Haq's time,

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:08.400
[Guest 2]: an article 62, which said that a person who is elected to the legislative assembly, he

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:14.040
[Guest 2]: should have adequate knowledge of Islamic teachings and practices on the obligatory

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:20.160
[Guest 2]: duties prescribed by Islam, and he should abstain from major sins. And the clause also

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:25.600
[Guest 2]: said that candidate should be sadiq and amin. So it means honest and righteous. Now you

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:32.680
[Guest 2]: can understand how vague this is. So the Pakistani military jihadi complex often uses this clause

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:39.240
[Guest 2]: to just take people out which whom they don't like, and the way they do now is very intelligent.

00:20:39.240 --> 00:20:46.160
[Guest 2]: So earlier, like back until the 1990s, they could just overthrow the political outfits

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:52.320
[Guest 2]: and the army guys could become the president and military martial law administrators like

00:20:52.320 --> 00:20:58.040
[Guest 2]: what Pervez Musharraf, Zia ul Haq and all those guys did. But now, there will be a backlash

00:20:58.040 --> 00:21:03.240
[Guest 2]: internationally even within Pakistan, right? So what they do is more intelligent things,

00:21:03.240 --> 00:21:08.520
[Guest 2]: more sophisticated things, they get the judiciary to front this. So the judiciary will say that,

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:14.880
[Guest 2]: okay, Nawaz Sharif has been involved in Panama paper leaks, and he is no longer sadiq and

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:20.680
[Guest 2]: amin. So he should be thrown off. And then you have this entire set of another guy coming

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:26.320
[Guest 2]: in who the Pakistani army wants, which is quite marvelous. Yeah, in fact, that's why

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:33.640
[Guest 1]: the recent dismissal of Nawaz Sharif and his putting an arrest out for him for 10 years,

00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:38.200
[Guest 1]: he's supposed to be jailed. It was called judicial coup, because that's what it was.

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:43.440
[Guest 1]: It was orchestrated by the Pakistan army. So the army basically controls the judiciary

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:48.280
[Amit Varma]: and uses it as a tool when it wants to. Yeah. So you know, I want to ask you guys about

00:21:48.280 --> 00:21:53.600
[Amit Varma]: the current elections. But before I do that, a slightly deeper question going back to the

00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:58.040
[Amit Varma]: background that you were giving me before the start of the episode about the army's

00:21:58.040 --> 00:22:04.040
[Amit Varma]: predominant role in Pakistani politics, which is so different from the army's role in India

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:11.840
[Amit Varma]: and thank goodness for that. And can you give me a TLDR of how the Pakistani army, the military

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:19.240
[Amit Varma]: jihadi complex as it has become now, became dominant in Pakistan politics right from 47.

00:22:19.240 --> 00:22:25.040
[Amit Varma]: And if that is a structural reason, then why should it change now? I mean, is there any

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:30.800
[Guest 2]: hope of it ever changing? Yeah, the structural reason for the Pakistan

00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:36.800
[Guest 2]: army's dominance was, now Pakistan was born a very insecure state, right? And it always

00:22:36.800 --> 00:22:43.440
[Guest 2]: perceived it so. So for the first few years, the biggest chunk of their budgetary allocation

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:49.320
[Guest 2]: was in defense itself. So, in a sense, it was the army and the armed forces which got

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:56.040
[Guest 2]: a head start over the other institutions. And in a fragile state, which was just beginning,

00:22:56.040 --> 00:23:01.960
[Guest 2]: it was only the army which sort of seemed to work, right? And remember, during the British

00:23:01.960 --> 00:23:08.320
[Guest 2]: times as well, they had allocated big canal colonies along the Indus and given it to the

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:13.480
[Guest 2]: military guys, etc. So, these were also the people who were the richer ones, the well-educated

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:20.280
[Guest 2]: ones, and now also more important from a public finance point of view. So, these people had

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:27.680
[Guest 2]: a head start and that sort of they then you had the first coup which came up and you had

00:23:27.680 --> 00:23:33.360
[Guest 2]: Ayub Khan taking over the reins. So, it was born that way, you know, and that sort of

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:41.480
[Guest 2]: has continued. The army has never allowed the other putative state to actually emerge.

00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:45.800
[Amit Varma]: And was it like, as in our case, was there ever a sort of constitution which tried to

00:23:45.800 --> 00:23:50.400
[Guest 2]: lay down the rules of the game? Or how did that go? Yeah, the often the constitution

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:57.120
[Guest 2]: was made by the army guys itself. After they ruled, they had a new constitution, it changed,

00:23:57.120 --> 00:24:05.200
[Guest 2]: etc. So, it always tried to give a veneer of democracy and a legitimacy which you would

00:24:05.200 --> 00:24:11.280
[Guest 2]: find acceptable, but always it was clear where the power center lay. And to your question

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:18.040
[Guest 2]: of whether it will change or not, the only thing sort of which can change is if this

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:23.920
[Guest 2]: Pakistani military jihadi complex is no longer seen as the one which can deliver the goods

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:30.120
[Guest 2]: for the Pakistanis. And I guess, at least the trend is now in a direction where Pakistanis

00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:36.860
[Guest 2]: themselves are questioning where we are going with what we've done. And, you know, the countries

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:42.440
[Guest 2]: around Pakistan have managed to do much better things. So, they are questioning that. And

00:24:42.440 --> 00:24:47.760
[Guest 2]: that's why you are seeing a lot of this civil unrest with the PTM, etc., which is coming

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:53.240
[Amit Varma]: up. And therein lies the hope, I guess. In fact, this is why I keep saying that, you

00:24:53.240 --> 00:24:56.640
[Amit Varma]: know, just because we view Pakistan as the enemy, which as you correctly pointed out,

00:24:56.640 --> 00:25:00.480
[Amit Varma]: there are two aspects of Pakistan and the military jihadi complex as enemy, just because

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:04.520
[Amit Varma]: of that, we shouldn't cut down on trade with them. In fact, if anything, we should expand

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:08.520
[Amit Varma]: free trade with them, we should expand person to person relations, because all of those

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:14.320
[Amit Varma]: things will only strengthen Pakistani civil society vis-a-vis the military jihadi complex.

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:17.960
[Amit Varma]: So that is sort of another front in the battle we have to fight against.

00:25:17.960 --> 00:25:23.640
[Guest 2]: Right. But I would say, I have a slightly different take to it, at least we shouldn't

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:30.480
[Guest 2]: think of all these big overtures, you know, a PM meeting a PM and all that, because the

00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:36.960
[Guest 2]: past evidence shows that whenever such big jhumlas take place, immediately after that,

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:41.760
[Guest 2]: the military jihadi complex strikes back. There is instance after instance where this

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:48.720
[Guest 2]: has happened. So, it's better to not, you know, insert a finger into the eyes of the

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:54.840
[Guest 2]: MJC by doing these big events. Yeah, you could do it at a first start with a back channel

00:25:54.840 --> 00:26:01.600
[Guest 2]: talks, NSAs to NSAs, and then slowly open people to people contacts, but anything which

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:06.640
[Guest 2]: is big, which questions the military jihadi complex, who's, you know, the foundation of

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:12.120
[Guest 2]: that is that they are going to protect against India, right? So, if you start to question

00:26:12.120 --> 00:26:17.000
[Amit Varma]: that, then MJC strikes back. So, like the MJC, maybe what you're saying is MJC may be

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:20.360
[Amit Varma]: wounded and insecure, but they're still the biggest beast in the room and you don't want

00:26:20.360 --> 00:26:25.880
[Amit Varma]: to roil them up too much. We'll shift to talking about the current elections, which I find

00:26:25.880 --> 00:26:30.200
[Amit Varma]: hopelessly complicated and hard to understand right after a brief commercial break.

